        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "SQA must demonstrate version control, regression testing covering hemolysis transport physics, and documented change control. Gradation 3 requires formal test plan with traceability matrix linking test cases to requirements."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "Method of manufactured solutions (MMS) applied to the incompressible Navier-Stokes solver and the hemolysis scalar transport equation. Observed order of accuracy (1.97 for velocity, 1.94 for hemolysis scalar) is consistent with the theoretical second-order scheme. Convergence plots and MMS source terms are archived in the verification report.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/code-verification-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "MMS or equivalent must demonstrate observed order of accuracy within 10% of theoretical order for all primary solution variables including the hemolysis scalar transport equation. Results must be archived with reproducible input files."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "Grid convergence index (GCI) study performed on three systematically refined meshes (4.2M, 11.8M, 31.4M cells) at the 4 L/min, 3000 RPM operating point. GCI for hemolysis index: 3.1% (fine-to-medium) and 8.7% (medium-to-coarse), confirming asymptotic convergence. The 11.8M mesh is used for production runs as the best balance of accuracy and cost. Discretization uncertainty is propagated into the Monte Carlo UQ.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/discretization-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "GCI study on minimum three mesh levels with refinement ratio ≥ 1.3. GCI on the quantity of interest (hemolysis index) must be < 10% on the production mesh. Asymptotic convergence ratio must be within [0.95, 1.05]."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "rationale": "In-vitro experiments were conducted at 12 of the 15 operating points within the declared envelope (flow rates 2–6 L/min, speeds 2400–3600 RPM). Test fluid was porcine blood at 38–42% hematocrit, temperature controlled to 37 ± 0.5 °C. Inlet/outlet pressures matched the declared envelope bounds. All boundary conditions were measured and documented with calibrated instrumentation (NIST-traceable). Test repeatability demonstrated across three independent runs per operating point (CV < 4% for hemolysis index).",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/test-conditions-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Test conditions must match the declared operating envelope with documented boundary condition measurements. Repeatability must be demonstrated with CV < 10% across replicate experiments. NIST-traceable calibration required for all measurement instruments."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "Quantitative comparison performed using validation metric (E/U_val) per ASME V&V 20. For hemolysis index, |E|/U_val < 1.0 at 10 of 12 validation points, indicating model is consistent with experimental data within combined experimental and numerical uncertainty. Mean normalized error across all points: 7.2%. Velocity field comparison via PIV shows R² > 0.90 at all measured cross-sections.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/output-comparison-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Validation metric |E|/U_val < 1.0 required at ≥ 80% of validation points. Mean normalized error for hemolysis index must be < 15%. Velocity field R² must exceed 0.85 at all PIV measurement planes."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "The primary quantity of interest (normalized index of hemolysis, NIH) is directly the clinical acceptance metric for VAD devices per ISO 10993-4 and FDA guidance. The CFD model outputs volume-averaged hemolysis scalar which maps directly to the NIH calculation. No surrogate or proxy QoI is used. The hemolysis power-law model (Giersiepen-Wurzinger) is applied consistently between simulation and experimental reduction.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/qoi-relevance-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "QoI must be the direct clinical acceptance metric (NIH) without surrogate substitution. The hemolysis model applied in CFD post-processing must match the model used for experimental NIH calculation."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "Validation experiments used the same FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry as the COU device (not a surrogate geometry). Operating conditions span the full declared envelope (2–6 L/min, 2400–3600 RPM). Test fluid (porcine blood) is physiologically representative of the clinical use fluid. The only deviation from COU conditions is the use of ex-vivo rather than in-vivo blood, which introduces a documented and bounded uncertainty of < 5% in NIH.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/validation-relevance-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Validation geometry must be identical or analytically equivalent to the COU device geometry. Operating conditions must span ≥ 80% of the declared envelope. Deviations from COU conditions must be documented with bounded uncertainty estimates."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "Iterative convergence monitored via residual norms (all < 1e-6) and global conservation checks (mass imbalance < 0.01%). Steady-state RANS simulations run to 10,000 iterations with residual plateau confirmed. For the hemolysis scalar, convergence of the volume-averaged NIH to < 0.1% change over final 1000 iterations is documented for all 15 operating points.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/solver-error-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Residual norms must reach < 1e-5. Mass imbalance must be < 0.1%. Volume-averaged NIH must converge to < 0.5% change over final 10% of iterations."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "Simulation workflow is documented in a controlled simulation plan with step-by-step procedures for mesh generation, boundary condition assignment, solver settings, and post-processing. Two independent analysts reproduced the NIH prediction at the 4 L/min, 3000 RPM operating point with < 1% discrepancy, confirming the workflow is unambiguous. Boundary condition inputs are read from a structured parameter file to eliminate manual entry errors.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/use-error-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Simulation plan must be documented with sufficient detail for independent reproduction. Independent reproduction at one representative operating point must yield < 5% discrepancy in NIH."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "The SST k-ω turbulence model is used, selected based on its demonstrated performance for confined rotating flows in the literature and confirmed by the validation comparison. The Giersiepen-Wurzinger hemolysis power-law model is applied as the standard for centrifugal pump hemolysis prediction. Model form uncertainty is estimated via comparison with the Bludszuweit model at 3 operating points, yielding a model form uncertainty of ±12% in NIH, which is incorporated into the Monte Carlo UQ.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/model-form-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Turbulence model selection must be justified by literature evidence or preliminary validation. Hemolysis model form uncertainty must be quantified by comparison with at least one alternative model and incorporated into the total uncertainty budget."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "All model inputs (blood viscosity, density, hematocrit, impeller geometry, rotational speed, inlet/outlet pressure boundary conditions) are characterized with documented uncertainty distributions. Viscosity: Carreau model parameters fit to rheometry data with 95% CI. Geometry: CMM measurements of impeller with ±0.02 mm tolerance. All 14 uncertain inputs are propagated through the model via 5000-sample Monte Carlo, yielding 95% prediction intervals on NIH at all operating points.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/model-inputs-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "All inputs with uncertainty > 1% effect on NIH must be characterized with probability distributions and propagated through Monte Carlo UQ. Geometry must be measured with documented tolerances. Monte Carlo sample size must be sufficient for 95% CI convergence (< 2% change in CI bounds with additional 500 samples)."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "Porcine blood samples sourced from a single abattoir, processed within 4 hours of collection. Hematocrit adjusted to 40 ± 2% by centrifugation. Sample characterization includes complete blood count, plasma free hemoglobin baseline (< 5 mg/dL), and viscosity measurement. Three independent blood batches used across the 12 experimental operating points to assess inter-batch variability (CV < 6% for NIH).",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/test-samples-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Blood samples must be characterized with CBC and baseline plasma free hemoglobin. Multiple independent batches required to assess inter-batch variability. CV for NIH across batches must be < 15%."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "Equivalency analysis performed comparing CFD boundary condition inputs to experimentally measured conditions at each of the 12 validation operating points. Inlet velocity profiles derived from upstream PIV measurements and applied as CFD boundary conditions. Pressure boundary conditions matched to within ± 1 mmHg of measured values. Rotational speed matched to within ± 5 RPM. A formal equivalency table documents the CFD input versus measured value for all 8 primary boundary condition parameters at all 12 operating points.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/input-equivalency-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Equivalency table required documenting CFD inputs versus measured experimental conditions for all primary boundary condition parameters. Pressure boundary conditions must match within ± 2 mmHg. Rotational speed must match within ± 10 RPM. Inlet velocity profile must be derived from measured data, not assumed uniform."
      }
    }
